<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="83944130ae65883552196d27d1f3ff66" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/articles/articles.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/articles/articles.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> A Guide to Weaponry Part 1: The Free Peoples<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.42)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10025'>Brad "Dr_Diablo" Peck</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10025&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> March 27, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Dwarf Culture<br />
The Dwarven Culture isn&#8217;t a favourite of  LotR players by any means.  The companions, except perhaps for Gimli, are not the strongest by any means, do not have too many methods of healing themselves, and really are lacking abilities that would make them useful.  However, with the MoM expansion just released, and a good chunk of cards dedicated to Dwarves, plus the new promotional card Book of Mazarbul, perhaps Dwarves will see a little more playability these days.  Lets take a look at the weapons they have to offer. <br />
<br />
Dwarven Axe &#8211; At zero twilight cost and strength +2 it isn&#8217;t very bad in terms of economical use.  But this card really shines in its text, which forces your opponent to discard one off the top of the draw deck after the bearer wins a skirmish.  LotR isn&#8217;t like Star Wars in the sense that the deck sizes are fixed and discarding would mean a great deal of pain, but if the bearer wins a skirmish at a lucky time, the opponent may lose that ever-important minion they were searching for.  Unfortunately it&#8217;s a Dwarf card, so good luck finding one at a tournament.<br />
<br />
Gimli&#8217;s Battle Axe &#8211; Gimli is the only Dwarf I&#8217;ve ever seen used in a competitive deck, and his weapon is well worth the price to pay.  At 2 twilight it is quite expensive for a character who, later down the road, is just going to be there to draw your opponents attacks away, but lets look at what it adds.  2 to strength, a damage +1 modifier and he can wound an Orc every time he wins a skirmish.  This card is perfect on any version of Gimli against a Sauron or Moria deck, as the minions will be killed because of his damage + 2 total, so you can wound and hopefully kill another Orc.  Problems arise when you&#8217;re fighting a Nazgul or Uruk-Hai deck, so the rare Gimli from the first set would be the prime choice.<br />
<br />
Hand Axe &#8211; The third installment of the Dwarven arsenal is the small Hand Axe.  At 0 twilight, its cheap, but only adds 1 to strength, and its ability of adding 1 to the archery total if its discarded isn&#8217;t particularly useful.  This is not a very effective card at all.<br />
<br />
<br />
Elf Culture<br />
The Elves themselves are not good at fighting, and it is highly recommended not to throw in any but Legolas, Arwen and possibly Hladir.  The Lorien Elves won&#8217;t be able to take the heat, and unless you devote your entire deck to archery, you won&#8217;t even need to use those guys.  Elven Culture has a few cards which work well in any deck, Legolas Greenleaf to shoot down the minions, Elrond to draw up some cards, and Galadriel and her Mirror.<br />
<br />
Bow of the Galadhrim &#8211; Any deck that uses Legolas is probably not using him for his brute strength, but his ability to &#8220;ping&#8221; the health right out of the minions using Legolas, Greenleaf.  This weapon adds 1 to strength, and lets you wound a minion each time Legolas wins a skirmish.  With this being the only weapon he can use, besides perhaps the Elven Bow, which is ineffective on him, you probably arent going to have him winning, or even being in any skirimshes.<br />
<br />
Elven Bow &#8211; This bow only has two reasons to be in your deck as far as this player can tell.  The first is that a lot of decks are starting Arwen and Legolas, and you may as well make Arwen an archer, so she isn&#8217;t just there to take the hits later on.  The other reason is that if you really want to, you can use Hladir during the last couple sites with it, since his strength will be higher, and he&#8217;ll be adding another to your archery total.  Most people only ever need two archers anyways&#8230; Aragorn and Legolas.<br />
<br />
Gwemegil &#8211; Upon first glance, I really saw no outstanding reason to use this card or Arwen in a deck.  But, as I played against my brother, he used this weapon to its complete usefulness.  Alright, its expensive, costing two twilight, but it adds 2 to Arwens strength and gives her the +1 damage modifier.  During a skirmish, you can exert her or discard two cards to add one to her strength.  What my brother had done was that he played with several copies of each weapon, armor, shield and so forth so that they were all played very quickly. He would throw the rest out to add to her power, so that she won more skirmishes, and he cycled through his deck very quickly.  Don&#8217;t underestimate the power of Arwen armed with this card.<br />
<br />
<br />
Gandalf Culture<br />
Unless you are devoting a large number of cards in your deck towards Gandalf, you shouldn&#8217;t use him.  When he&#8217;s loaded with his Staff and Glamdring, plus a few of his spells that allow for non-exertion, non-wounding, or lowering the opponents stength, then he&#8217;s a tank.  Plus, if he goes into site 5 at full vitality with his staff, he can exert four times to take the Balrog.<br />
<br />
Glamdring &#8211; This is really the only weapon Gandalf can use since I really don&#8217;t count his staff as a weapon, but make sure that you equip him with both of these weapons.  During the Fellowship phase, if you had just laid down all your forces and know that upon moving to the next site, the opponent is going to have a huge amount of twilight tokens, exert him to remove one token per Orc you find there.  This is even more effective if you also use Sting to check, so you can remove a lot of the tokens, and prevent an Orc beatdown.  Its also useful to know how many minions your opponent has before you move, so you can prepare for your double move.<br />
<br />
<br />
Gondor Culture<br />
By far the most commonly seen companions, besides Frodo of course, are the two men of Gondor.  Keep in mind that if you want to use Boromir as a ranger, your going to have to use the rare one.  If you load these guys up with armor, their swords, Boromir with his shield, and Aragorn with his Bow, your deck is going to flow smoothly.<br />
<br />
Aragorn&#8217;s Bow &#8211; This card is probably the biggest pile of cheese ever.  Exert Aragorn to wound a minion?  gosh darnit, I think they should have reconsidered, knowing this ranger can bust out some Versatility and leave every minion with only 1 vitality anyways, and being able to &#8220;ping&#8221; off three of them.  Combine this with Legolas Greenleaf, and you aren&#8217;t going to be touched at any of the rivers in the game.<br />
<br />
Blade of Gondor &#8211; Boromir is a tough guy.  Play the rare one and there&#8217;s pretty much no way in hell that he&#8217;s going to be overwhelmed.  This weapon adds 2 to his strength, and the damage +1 modifier.  But that isn&#8217;t all.  If Boromir&#8217;s two damage to an Orc or an Uruk-Hai isnt enough, just exert him once or twice and he can bring the house down.  <br />
<br />
Flaming Brand &#8211; The Gondor Men got a big boost with this card, even though against any culture besides Nazgul it is not very effective accept that it adds 1 to strength.  But, when your fighting a Nazgul bearer is strength +2 and damage +1, so almost any nazgul accept the Witch-King will be taking the heat&#8230;. Literally.  And even against him you&#8217;ll be able to give him a good fight.<br />
<br />
Ranger&#8217;s Sword &#8211; Theres no special modifiers on this sword, just the standard 2 to strength and plus 1 damage, but if Aragorn isnt already a problem with his 8 strength, well he will be with 10.  This, his bow and a flaming brand will make for a very hard to kill ranger.<br />
<br />
<br />
Shire Culture<br />
Last but not least is the Hobbiton Culture.  Many players who haven&#8217;t played an effective Hobbit deck will not know what power these guys actually have.  The different variants of each Hobbit (as can be seen in an upcoming article by yours truly) are very helpful in certain situations.  And when pumped up with a weapon, they can all last until site 9, though Pippin usually bites the dust there.<br />
<br />
Hobbit Sword &#8211; This weapon doesn&#8217;t seem all useful, since all it does really is add 2 to a Hobbits power.  However, when you factor in that Hobbits have their allies to keep them alive much longer, and this sword will boost their power so that when you use Bounders, the opponent needs a lot of strength to overwhelm them.  Also, it makes Merry a nice power 7, which will be very useful in an all-Hobbit deck.<br />
<br />
Sting &#8211; Sting should be in every deck because it&#8217;s a simple way of removing twilight after you&#8217;ve played a lot of cards, or to remove the twilight from the pool before that important double-jump.  Alright, if your opponents playing Uruks or Nazguls they won&#8217;t have to remove any twilight, but if you know their deck is loaded with Goblins you&#8217;ll be glad to see their hand and remove some twilight.  This or Glamdring could work well with an Elven deck that uses Curse Their Foul Feet! so you can see how many minions they usually have in their hand, and use CTFF! on your turn.<br />
<br />
<br />
Overall Usefulness of the Weapons<br />
Alright, so maybe most people look at Gimli and decide that he&#8217;s not good enough for the deck, or decide that they don&#8217;t want to put any Flaming Brands in because they may not face any Ringwraiths.  You are all welcome to your own personal preferences, but in my opinion, here are some deck ideas, and what weapons they should be using.<br />
<br />
Rangers and Legolas Deck:  Most of these decks are going to start with Arwen and Legolas, use Prancing Pony as their opening site, and run three copies of Boromir, and three of Aragorn just in case.  This deck obviously needs to also have a couple Rangers Sword, a couple Blade of Gondor, and a couple Gwemegil.  Sting is also a suggestion, but you shouldn&#8217;t make your deck to large, so if it doesn&#8217;t fit well, don&#8217;t worry about it.  If you think its helpful, add in an Elven Bow for Arwen.<br />
<br />
All-Hobbit Deck: You&#8217;re going to need to use Sting and three Hobbit Swords, though I suggest throwing in four, because you&#8217;re going to need Merry to get one ASAP. <br />
<br />
Dwarven Deck: Though probably something you could completely ignore, these decks do exist, so I wrote this for you guys.  The best Dwarven Decks I&#8217;ve seen start with Gimli (the rare from the first set) and Gloin.  Gloin may look like a wussy, but if you throw down 4 Stairs of Khazad-Dum, a Greatest Kingdom of My People, and a Till Durin Wakes Again he&#8217;s going to be pumped up.  You&#8217;re going to need Gimli&#8217;s Axe for sure, and for Gloin, Farin, Fror, and any Dwarf Guards you may want, be sure to throw in four Dwarven Axe.  Hand Axes aren&#8217;t terribly useful, so you can ignore them.<br />
<br />
Any deck with Gandalf: Any deck with him should throw in multiple copies of Glamdring and Gandalf&#8217;s Staff (I didn&#8217;t write about it because its not really a weapon) just because when he&#8217;s got both on, he is going to be one of your best warriors.  Unfortunately for Gandalf, he hasn&#8217;t been given as many other possessions as Boromir or Aragorn have.<br />
